# 2. Architecture Overview

## 2.1 The Big Picture

ELECTRON-2 is one agent in a larger multi-agent system called the
QUANTUM AI Content Factory. The full system has 4 agents. ELECTRON-2 is
fully operational and ELECTRON-1 pipeline is built (Day 10):

-   **QUANTUM:** QUANTUM --- Orchestrator and final QA authority
    (prompts written Day 7, workflow planned for future)

-   **ELECTRON-1:** ELECTRON-1 --- Trend discovery agent (Phase 4, IN
    PROGRESS --- 9-node pipeline built Day 10)

-   **ELECTRON-2:** ELECTRON-2 --- Content writer and QA pipeline (THIS
    DOCUMENT) ✔️

-   **ELECTRON-3:** ELECTRON-3 --- Video producer and publisher (Phase
    5, Days 13-15)

## 2.2 Hybrid RAG Architecture

The pipeline uses a hybrid approach combining two types of knowledge:

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **STATIC CORE (\~1,200 words)**     **DYNAMIC KNOWLEDGE (from Qdrant)**
  ----------------------------------- -----------------------------------
  Hardcoded in Assemble Prompt node.  Pulled at runtime from Qdrant
  Defines WHO the agent is and HOW it vector database. Tells WHAT to
  works. Never changes. Includes:     follow. Changes and grows over
  agent identity, output format with  time. Includes: brand colors,
  emoji headers, workflow steps       fonts, visual guidelines,
  (Parse \> Plan \> Create \> Check), platform-specific tone rules,
  safe framing rules.                 module definitions, 71 banned
                                      phrases.

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

> 💡 *Analogy: The static core is like a chef\'s training and cooking
> technique (doesn\'t change). The dynamic knowledge is like today\'s
> menu and ingredient restrictions (changes regularly). You don\'t
> retrain the chef every time you add a new dish --- you just update the
> menu.*

## 2.3 Pipeline Flow (15 Nodes)

The complete pipeline flows left-to-right in n8n:

> Manual Trigger → Parse Brief → CorpFit Qdrant → Get Banned Phrases →
>
> Assemble Prompt → Call Claude API → Parse Output → Banned Phrase Check
> →
>
> QA Gate 1 Health → QA Gate 2 Brand → QA Gate 3 Audience →
>
> Format for Storage → Store to content_logs
>
> (+ 2 Embedding nodes: Embeddings Ollama, Embeddings Ollama1)

# 3. Node-by-Node Reference

Every node in the ELECTRON-2 pipeline, explained in detail.

## Node 1: Manual Trigger

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Type**          Manual Trigger (n8n built-in)
  ----------------- -----------------------------------------------------
  **Purpose**       Starts the pipeline when you click \'Execute
                    workflow\'

  **Input**         None (human clicks the button)

  **Output**        Empty trigger signal that starts the chain

  **Added**         Day 3
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

In the future, this will be replaced by a QUANTUM schedule trigger
(cron) that runs automatically on a daily or weekly schedule.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Node 2: Parse Brief

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Type**          Set Node (manual fields)
  ----------------- -----------------------------------------------------
  **Purpose**       Defines the content brief --- WHAT to create

  **Input**         Trigger signal from Node 1

  **Output**        JSON object with 5 fields: module, platform, funnel,
                    topic, duration

  **Added**         Day 4
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

### Fields

-   **module:** module --- Which CorpFit module: steps, workouts, meals,
    checkin, events

-   **platform:** platform --- Target platform: tiktok, instagram,
    linkedin, youtube

-   **funnel:** funnel --- Audience type: b2c (individuals) or b2b
    (corporate HR)

-   **topic:** topic --- The content subject, e.g. \'3 simple habits to
    sleep better tonight\'

-   **duration:** duration --- Video length: \'30 seconds\', \'60
    seconds\', etc.

> 💡 *In the future, ELECTRON-1 will auto-generate briefs from trending
> topics and feed them here.*

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Node 3: CorpFit Qdrant (Brand Rules)

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Type**          Qdrant Vector Store Retrieval
  ----------------- -----------------------------------------------------
  **Purpose**       Retrieves the most relevant brand rules for this
                    specific brief

  **Collection**    corpfit_brand_rules (44 entries)

  **Input**         The topic from Parse Brief, converted to a vector via
                    Embeddings Ollama

  **Output**        \~15 most relevant brand rule chunks (text snippets)

  **Embedding       nomic-embed-text (via Ollama container)
  Model**           

  **Added**         Day 4
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

This node connects to the Embeddings Ollama sub-node which converts the
topic text into a 768-dimensional vector. Qdrant then finds the 15 brand
rule entries most semantically similar to the topic.

> 💡 *The brand rules include: CorpFit personality traits,
> platform-specific tone guidelines, color codes (#FF6B35 Coral, #004E89
> Blue), module definitions, safe/unsafe framing language, and more.*

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Node 4: Get Banned Phrases

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Type**          Qdrant Vector Store Retrieval
  ----------------- -----------------------------------------------------
  **Purpose**       Retrieves banned phrases relevant to this content
                    topic

  **Collection**    corpfit_banned_phrases (71 entries)

  **Input**         The topic from Parse Brief, converted via Embeddings
                    Ollama1

  **Output**        Most relevant banned phrase entries for downstream
                    checking

  **Added**         Day 4
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

Banned phrases include words and phrases CorpFit content must never use,
such as body-shaming language, aggressive fitness terminology,
unqualified medical claims, and competitor brand names.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Node 5: Assemble Prompt

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Type**          Code Node (JavaScript)
  ----------------- -----------------------------------------------------
  **Purpose**       Combines the static core prompt with dynamic Qdrant
                    knowledge into one mega-prompt

  **Input**         Brief from Parse Brief + brand rules from Qdrant +
                    banned phrases from Qdrant

  **Output**        One assembled prompt string (\~3,300 words) ready for
                    Claude API

  **Added**         Day 4
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

### What It Builds

The assembled prompt has this structure:

1.  **Section 1 ---** Agent identity: \'You are ELECTRON-2, the Content
    Creation Specialist for CorpFit\'

2.  **Section 2 ---** The 10-layer UAF-1.0 framework (Universal Agent
    Framework) with workflow steps

3.  **Section 3 ---** Dynamic brand rules retrieved from Qdrant
    (injected here)

4.  **Section 4 ---** Dynamic banned phrases retrieved from Qdrant
    (injected here)

5.  **Section 5 ---** Output format specification with emoji headers for
    structured parsing

6.  **Section 6 ---** The production brief: topic, platform, module,
    funnel, duration

> 💡 *This is the hybrid RAG in action: Sections 1, 2, 5 are static
> (hardcoded). Sections 3, 4 are dynamic (from Qdrant). Section 6 is the
> specific request.*

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Node 6: Call Claude API

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Type**          Code Node (JavaScript)
  ----------------- -----------------------------------------------------
  **Purpose**       Sends the assembled prompt to Claude Sonnet 4 and
                    receives generated content

  **Model**         claude-sonnet-4-20250514

  **API Endpoint**  https://api.anthropic.com/v1/messages

  **Max Tokens**    4096

  **Cost**          \~\$0.005 per content piece

  **HTTP Method**   this.helpers.httpRequest() (NOT fetch, NOT \$http)

  **Added**         Day 4
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

The node sends the full assembled prompt to Claude Sonnet 4 and receives
a structured response with emoji-delimited sections. The response
typically contains \~1,500 tokens of generated content.

> ⚠️ *CRITICAL: n8n Code nodes do NOT support fetch() or \$http. You
> MUST use this.helpers.httpRequest(). This was a major discovery on Day
> 4 that cost hours of debugging.*

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Node 7: Parse Output

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Type**          Code Node (JavaScript)
  ----------------- -----------------------------------------------------
  **Purpose**       Parses Claude\'s raw text response into structured
                    JSON fields

  **Input**         Raw text from Claude API containing emoji-delimited
                    sections

  **Output**        Flat JSON with individual fields: topic, module,
                    platform, hooks, script, etc.

  **Added**         Day 5
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

### Parsed Fields

Claude responds with emoji headers like 🎬 HOOKS, 📝 SCRIPT, etc. This
node extracts each section into its own field:

-   brief_summary, hooks, script, on_screen_text, storyboard,
    caption_short, caption_long, cta, disclaimer, self_check

-   Plus metadata: topic, module, platform, funnel, duration (passed
    through from brief)

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Node 8: Banned Phrase Check

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Type**          Code Node (JavaScript)
  ----------------- -----------------------------------------------------
  **Purpose**       Scans all content fields for banned phrases (first
                    safety layer)

  **Input**         Parsed content fields from Node 7

  **Output**        All content fields + banned_check_passed
                    (true/false) + flagged_phrases array

  **Added**         Day 5
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

This is a simple text-matching check against the 71 banned phrases from
Qdrant. It\'s a fast, deterministic first filter before the more
expensive AI-powered QA gates.

> 💡 *Think of it as a metal detector at the airport entrance (fast,
> catches obvious issues). The QA gates are like the detailed luggage
> scanner (slower, catches subtle issues).*

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Nodes 9-11: QA Gate System (3 Gates)

These are the AI-powered quality assurance gates. Each gate calls Claude
Haiku with a specialized prompt, parses the response, and passes all
data through to the next gate. If any gate fails, the content is
ultimately marked as BLOCKED.

All 3 gates follow the same code pattern (see Section 4 for details):

7.  Read all fields from \$json (flat data from previous node)

8.  Build a specialized system prompt for this gate\'s focus

9.  Build a user message containing the content to review

10. Call Claude Haiku via this.helpers.httpRequest()

11. Parse JSON response with robust fallback (regex rescue on failure)

12. Copy ALL original fields to output + append gate results

### Node 9: QA Gate 1 --- Health Claims

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Focus**         Medical claims, guaranteed outcomes, unsafe advice
  ----------------- -----------------------------------------------------
  **Stance**        STRICT on medical claims, LENIENT on general wellness
                    encouragement

  **Output Fields** gate1_result, gate1_confidence, gate1_violations,
                    gate1_notes
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

### Node 10: QA Gate 2 --- Brand & Tone

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Focus**         Brand voice compliance, platform tone match, Fun Test
                    (1-5 score)
  ----------------- -----------------------------------------------------
  **Stance**        Verifies CorpFit personality: Supportive Coach, Fun
                    Friend, Reliable Guide

  **Output Fields** gate2_result, gate2_confidence, gate2_fun_score,
                    gate2_violations, gate2_notes
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

### Node 11: QA Gate 3 --- Audience Fit

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Focus**         Module-content alignment, funnel tone match, platform
                    format fit
  ----------------- -----------------------------------------------------
  **Stance**        Ensures B2C is fun/personal, B2B is
                    professional/ROI-focused

  **Output Fields** gate3_result, gate3_confidence, gate3_violations,
                    gate3_notes
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

Gate 3 also computes the FINAL DECISION:

-   **qa_decision:** qa_decision: \'APPROVED\' or \'BLOCKED\' (all 3
    gates must PASS for APPROVED)

-   **qa_quality_score:** qa_quality_score: average confidence across
    all 3 gates

-   **qa_fun_score:** qa_fun_score: from Gate 2 (1-5 scale)

-   **qa_failed_gate:** qa_failed_gate: which gate failed first (or
    \'NONE\')

-   **qa_approval_token:** qa_approval_token: \'PKT-YYYY-MM-DD-NNN\'
    format (or \'NONE\' if blocked)

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Node 12: Format for Storage

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Type**          Code Node (JavaScript)
  ----------------- -----------------------------------------------------
  **Purpose**       Maps all pipeline fields to PostgreSQL column names

  **Input**         Full data from Gate 3 (all content + all gate
                    results)

  **Output**        Clean JSON matching exact PostgreSQL content_logs
                    schema

  **Pipeline        v6 (set in this node)
  Version**         

  **Added**         Day 6 (updated Day 9)
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

### Key Mappings

-   qa_passed: true if qa_decision === \'APPROVED\'

-   qa_status: \'approved\' or \'blocked\'

-   qa_violations: JSON.stringify of all violations from all 3 gates
    combined

-   qa_violations_count: total count across all gates

-   approval_token: PKT token or \'NONE\'

-   status: \'approved\' or \'blocked\'

-   model: \'claude-sonnet-4-20250514\'

-   pipeline_version: \'v6\'

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Node 13: Store to content_logs

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Type**          PostgreSQL Insert Node (n8n built-in)
  ----------------- -----------------------------------------------------
  **Purpose**       Writes the final content + QA results to PostgreSQL
                    database

  **Table**         content_logs

  **Connection**    postgres:5432 (Docker container name, NOT localhost)

  **Database**      corpfit

  **Added**         Day 6
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Nodes 14-15: Embedding Sub-Nodes

These are helper nodes used by the Qdrant vector store nodes (Nodes 3
and 4). They convert text into 768-dimensional vectors using the
nomic-embed-text model running in the Ollama Docker container.

-   **Node 14:** Embeddings Ollama --- converts topic text for CorpFit
    Qdrant (brand rules) search

-   **Node 15:** Embeddings Ollama1 --- converts topic text for Get
    Banned Phrases search

Both connect to Ollama at http://ollama:11434 (Docker container name).

# 4. QA Gate System Deep Dive

## 4.1 Why Inline Gates (Not Sub-Workflow)

Originally (Day 8-9), the QA gates were built as a separate QUANTUM QA
Reviewer workflow with 14 nodes. ELECTRON-2 called it using n8n\'s
Execute Sub-Workflow node. However, a critical bug was discovered: the
sub-workflow trigger received items but with EMPTY JSON payloads. All
content fields arrived as empty strings.

After extensive debugging (testing \$json, \$input.all(),
\$input.first().json, and adding debug_keys/debug_count diagnostics),
the root cause was identified as n8n\'s sub-workflow data passing
limitation --- the trigger node receives item count but not the actual
JSON content.

The solution: move all 3 QA gates inline as Code nodes directly inside
ELECTRON-2. This eliminated the data passthrough issue entirely since
data never leaves the workflow context. The standalone QUANTUM QA
Reviewer workflow remains available for future refactoring once n8n\'s
sub-workflow behavior is better understood.

## 4.2 Gate 1 Tuning Story

The initial Gate 1 prompt said \'You are STRICT. When in doubt, FLAG
IT.\' This caused legitimate wellness content to be blocked:

-   Sleep tips blocked for \'missing disclaimers\' (Category D)

-   Step counting blocked for \'implicit health claims\' (Category E)

-   Phrases like \'actually work\' flagged as guaranteed outcomes

The fix: changed the stance to \'STRICT on medical claims but LENIENT on
general wellness encouragement\' and added explicit DO NOT FLAG rules
for general wellness tips, encouraging movement, fun motivational
language, and missing disclaimers on non-medical content.

> ⚠️ *Key lesson: QA gates need to understand the CONTEXT of the
> platform. A wellness app encouraging walking is fundamentally
> different from a medical website prescribing treatment. The gate
> prompt must reflect this.*

## 4.3 Robust JSON Parser

Every gate includes a robust JSON parser that handles Claude Haiku\'s
sometimes messy output:

13. **Step 1:** Strip markdown code fences (\`\`\`json \... \`\`\`) that
    Haiku sometimes adds

14. **Step 2:** Find JSON boundaries (first \'{\' to last \'}\')

15. **Step 3:** Attempt JSON.parse()

16. **Step 4:** If parse fails, regex rescue: search for
    \'\"result\":\"PASS\"\' in raw text

17. **Step 5:** If PASS found, construct a valid PASS response (prevents
    false blocks from malformed JSON)

18. **Step 6:** If FAIL or no match, return FAIL with PARSE_ERROR
    violation

## 4.4 Cost Per Gate

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Gate**                **Model**               **Cost/Call**
  ----------------------- ----------------------- -----------------------
  Gate 1: Health Claims   Claude Haiku 4.5        \~\$0.001

  Gate 2: Brand Tone      Claude Haiku 4.5        \~\$0.001

  Gate 3: Audience Fit    Claude Haiku 4.5        \~\$0.001
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

All 3 gates run sequentially (not in parallel) on every content piece.
Total QA cost: \~\$0.003 per piece.

# 5. Data Flow --- How Data Transforms

This section shows what data looks like at each stage of the pipeline.

## Stage 1: Parse Brief Output

> { module: \"steps\", platform: \"tiktok\", funnel: \"b2c\",
>
> topic: \"fun ways to hit 10000 steps\", duration: \"30 seconds\" }

## Stage 2: After Qdrant Retrieval

> Same brief fields + 15 brand rule chunks + banned phrase chunks

## Stage 3: After Assemble Prompt

> One massive prompt string (\~3,300 words) ready for Claude API

## Stage 4: After Claude API

> Raw text with emoji headers: 🎬 HOOKS: \... 📝 SCRIPT: \...

## Stage 5: After Parse Output

> { topic, module, platform, funnel, duration, brief_summary,
>
> hooks, script, on_screen_text, storyboard, caption_short,
>
> caption_long, cta, disclaimer, self_check }

## Stage 6: After Banned Phrase Check

> Same fields + banned_check_passed: true/false + flagged_phrases: \[\]

## Stage 7: After QA Gate 1

> Same fields + gate1_result, gate1_confidence, gate1_violations,
> gate1_notes

## Stage 8: After QA Gate 2

> Same fields + gate2_result, gate2_confidence, gate2_fun_score,
> gate2_violations

## Stage 9: After QA Gate 3

> Same fields + gate3_result + qa_decision, qa_quality_score,
> qa_fun_score,
>
> qa_failed_gate, qa_approval_token

## Stage 10: After Format for Storage

> Clean PostgreSQL-ready JSON with all 28 columns mapped

# 6. PostgreSQL Database Schema

All content is stored in the content_logs table in the corpfit database.

## 6.1 Connection Details

-   **Host:** Host: postgres (Docker container name)

-   **Port:** Port: 5432

-   **Database:** Database: corpfit

-   **Auth:** User/Password: configured in Docker compose

## 6.2 content_logs Table (28 Columns)

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Column**            **Type**    **Description**
  --------------------- ----------- ----------------------------------------
  id                    SERIAL PK   Auto-incrementing primary key

  module                VARCHAR     steps, workouts, meals, checkin, events

  platform              VARCHAR     tiktok, instagram, linkedin, youtube

  funnel                VARCHAR     b2c or b2b

  topic                 TEXT        The content topic/subject

  duration              VARCHAR     Video duration (30 seconds, etc.)

  brief_summary         TEXT        Generated content summary

  hooks                 TEXT        Video hook options

  script                TEXT        Full video script

  on_screen_text        TEXT        Text overlays for video

  storyboard            TEXT        Scene-by-scene visual guide

  caption_short         TEXT        Short caption for feed

  caption_long          TEXT        Detailed caption with hashtags

  cta                   TEXT        Call to action

  disclaimer            TEXT        Health/legal disclaimers

  self_check            TEXT        Agent\'s self-assessment

  qa_passed             BOOLEAN     true = APPROVED, false = BLOCKED

  qa_violations_count   INTEGER     Total violations across all 3 gates

  qa_violations         JSONB       Detailed violation objects (category,
                                    severity, fix)

  qa_status             VARCHAR     \'approved\' or \'blocked\'

  raw_content           TEXT        Reserved for raw Claude response

  generated_at          TIMESTAMP   When content was generated

  qa_checked_at         TIMESTAMP   When QA review completed

  status                VARCHAR     Lifecycle status (approved/blocked)

  approval_token        VARCHAR     PKT-YYYY-MM-DD-NNN or NONE

  pipeline_version      VARCHAR     v6 (current)

  model                 VARCHAR     claude-sonnet-4-20250514
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

The table has 6 indexes for fast querying on: id, module, platform,
status, qa_passed, and generated_at.

